riculum For The 21st Century: Theory, Policy and Practice</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I001646/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Scotland?s Curriculum for Excellence (CfE) is a good example of a new model for curriculum development, combining the central specification of a curriculum framework by government bodies with professional engagement by practitioners in schools and colleges. A series of four seminars, hosted by the School of Education, University of Stirling, and organised by Dr Mark Priestley and Prof Gert Biesta, aims to support critical engagement with this curriculum model.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The seminars aim to facilitate dialogue between educators and educationalists, applying established and new curriculum theory to the ongoing practical issues faced by a variety of professionals seeking to engage with CfE and similar curricula.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The seminars are focused on four key issues and feature prominent speakers with expertise in the areas in question:&lt;/p>

&lt;ul>
 

 &lt;li>Knowledge and the Curriculum&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Pedagogy and the Curriculum&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Assessment and the Curriculum&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>Curriculum Change and Teacher Development&lt;/li>

&lt;/ul>

